    <body.head>
      <hedline>
        <hl1>Social Security: Are Stocks Safe?</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Letter from Gerta Chamberlain says main concern to wage earners who would be allowed to invest percentage of Social Security tax in stock market is what would happen if market is down at time they retire</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''Benefits and Drawbacks to Bush and Gore Proposals for Overhauling Social Security'' (news article, May 19):</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''Benefits and Drawbacks to Bush and Gore Proposals for Overhauling Social Security'' (news article, May 19):</p>
        <p>The main question I've heard about allowing wage earners to invest a percentage of the Social Security tax in the stock market is, What will happen if the market is down at the time they retire?</p>
        <p>I share that concern. And I also wonder: What if a worker is forced to retire at an early age because of total disability and the market is down at that time? If a worker dies prematurely, what happens to the surviving family when the market is down? How are his or her payments affected?</p>
        <p>GERTA CHAMBERLAIN  West Orange, N.J., May 21, 2000</p>
      </block>
    </body.content>
